{{Quote|<nowiki></nowiki>''Mando'ade'' usually bury in mass graves anyway. We all become part of the ''manda''. We don't need a headstone.''"<br />"''<nowiki></nowiki>''Manda''.''"<br />"''Collective consciousness. Oversoul. We don't do heaven.|[[Mirta Gev]] and [[Boba Fett/Legends|Boba Fett]]|<ref name="Sacrifice">''[[Legacy of the Force: Sacrifice]]''</ref>}}
The '''''manda''''' was a spiritual<ref name="TMPaC">{{InsiderCite|86|The Mandalorians: People and Culture}}</ref> and philosophical concept in the [[Mandalorian religion]]. Among the living, ''manda'' referred to a state of being, wherein a Mandalorian had achieved a philosophical unity of mind, body, and spirit. Additionally, the ''manda'' could refer to the collective soul of the Mandalorian people, with Mandalorians passing into the ''manda'' upon their death.<ref name="TCSWE">''[[The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia]]''</ref>

Differing from the [[Mandalorian Crusaders|ancient]] [[Mandalorian Neo-Crusaders/Legends|Mandalorians']] belief in a literal afterlife, the metaphysical ''manda'' was best described as an oversoul,<ref name="Sacrifice" /> a collective state of being for all [[Mandalorian/Legends|Mandalorian]] souls upon [[Death/Legends|death]].

To be part of it, a Mandalorian was required to not only understand their culture as defined by the ''[[Resol'nare]]'', but truly live out its ideals in their lives. Mandalorians who did not live by the ''Resol'nare'' were considered to be ''dar'manda''&mdash;soulless, someone who was ignorant of their heritage and thus had no place in the Mandalorian afterlife. The state of being ''dar'manda'' was regarded as a fate worse than [[Death/Legends|death]] in the Mandalorian community.<ref name="TMPaC" />

The Mandalorian belief in the collective afterlife of the ''manda'' was of notable influence to their [[Burial/Legends|burial]] practices.<ref name="Sacrifice" /> Though the Mandalorians typically preferred [[Cremation/Legends|cremation]],<ref name="TMPaC" /> when burying the fallen in large numbers, Mandalorians would dig large, mass graves in which to lay their dead to rest.

Though many [[Species/Legends|species]] considered the prospect of unmarked mass graves horrid,<ref name="Sacrifice" /> Mandalorians believed that the body was merely a tool for doing deeds and passing on knowledge, and once the soul had gone to the ''manda'', what happened to the body was ultimately irrelevant.<ref name="TC">''[[Republic Commando: True Colors]]''</ref> Burying their people together in mass graves mirrored the collective consciousness every Mandalorian was believed to share in the ''manda'' after death.<ref name="Sacrifice" />

==Behind the scenes==
The ''manda'' was first introduced to ''[[Star Wars]]'' [[canon]] in ''[[The Mandalorians: People and Culture]]'' article, written by [[Author/Legends|author]] [[Karen Traviss]] for the [[Star Wars Insider 86|eighty-sixth]] issue of ''[[Star Wars Insider]]'' magazine, published [[February]] [[2006]]. The ''manda'' was later mentioned again in several entries in Traviss' [[Republic Commando|''Republic'' and ''Imperial Commando'']] novel series, including [[Republic Commando: True Colors|''True Colors'']], [[Order 66: A Republic Commando Novel|''Order 66'']], and ''[[Imperial Commando: 501st]]''. Traviss again mentioned the ''manda'' in two of her entries into the multi-author ''[[Star Wars: Legacy of the Force]]'' novel series, entitled ''[[Legacy of the Force: Sacrifice]]'' and ''[[Legacy of the Force: Revelation]]''.

